      {
        "id": 2158306,
        "name": "Xavier Lavoipierre",
        "username": "Xavier_Lavoipierre",
        "avatar_template": "/user_avatar/www.wineberserkers.com/xavier_lavoipierre/{size}/1432_2.png",
        "created_at": "2017-04-04T15:38:48.000Z",
        "cooked": "<p>Rob, check out Strava for riding options. One suggestion would be to get yourself to the intersection of Highway 29 and Trancas/Redwood. Take Redwood Road west to Dry Creek Road and take that north (easy uphill grade) until you get to Oakville Grade. Take a left and then another left after a few hundred meters onto Mt. Veeder Road, which will take you back to the town of Napa. It\u2019s a nice climb for a few miles, and then a ripping downhill. Very nice.</p>\n<p>Another suggestion, which may have been mentioned above, is if you\u2019re on the Silverado Trail you can take Howell Mtn. Road up, and then take a left when you get up to Deer Park Road. Another ripping downhill to the Trail. Or, you can make a right on Deer Park if you want to go to Angwin and beyond.</p>\n<p>And there\u2019s always the Oakville Grade if you\u2019re up for a challenge. Actually, with the Dry Creek Road option above, you can make a right onto Oakville Grade and have a fairly brief amount of climbing before heading <em><strong>down</strong></em> the Grade. Warning: it\u2019s very steep, and you can easily hit 50 mph in a hurry.</p>\n<p>A final suggestion, ride all the way up Hwy. 29 through Calistoga, then continue straight on Hwy. 128. Short and relatively easy climb over to the Alexander Valley. You can then go to Jimtown, or Chalk Hill Rd., or if you really want a longer ride and a challenge, Pine Flat or the Geysers. If you want to do the latter without all the pre-ride, just drive over the hill and start your ride at Jimtown. By the way, the Geysers is amazing. A great ride.</p>\n<p>Have fun!</p>",
